&#xa0;
[normal]National Housing Federation – Written evidence[bold]1.1
[normal] 
[normal]The National Housing Federation is the voice of affordable housing in England. We believe that everyone should have the home they need at a price they can afford. That’s why we represent the work of housing associations and campaign for better housing. Our members provide two and a half million homes for more than five million people. Each year they invest in a diverse range of neighbourhood projects that help create strong, vibrant communities.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.2
[normal] 
[normal]We welcome the opportunity to submit our evidence for the Draft Deregulation Bill. The bill proposes to reduce the eligibility period for the right to buy from five years to three years. We believe that the bill must accompanied by a number of other key changes if the right to buy’s impact on housing associations is to be mitigated. Our key concerns are:
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]1.2.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Government did not effectively consult[bold] over substantial increases in right to buy discounts especially in London and did not consider the impact on housing associations or the supply of affordable homes.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]1.2.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]There is no system in place to monitor[bold] the impact of the Preserved Right to 
[normal]Buy
[normal] upon the supply of affordable homes. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]1.2.3
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]There is no effective plan in place to replace affordable homes[bold] lost through the Preserved Right to Buy.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.3
[normal] 
[normal]The Joint Committee should recommend legislation be amended to:
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]1.3.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Protect Preserved Right to Buy Receipts ([bold]PRtB[bold]) [bold]so that local authorities are required to spend their receipts on funding new affordable homes.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.3.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Incorporate debt within the cost floor [bold]so the right to buy discount will be reduced if the sales receipt does not cover debt secured against a property. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.4
[normal] 
[normal]The Joint Committee should call on Government to:
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]1.4.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Carry out an independent right to buy review [bold]that takes into account recent evidence and develops more effective ways to build replacement affordable homes.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]1.4.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Put in place 
[normal]an effective system for regularly monitoring the preserved right to buy [bold]sales and the number of homes being replaced.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.5
[normal] 
[normal]Failure to act will result in the right to buy damaging housing association businesses and harming the Government’s ambitions to increase the supply of homes. 
[normal]2.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Right to buy legislation provides local authority tenants and some housing association tenants (approx. 620,000) with the right to buy their home at a discounted price. In April 
[normal]2012, the discount was increased to £75,000 or 70% for a flat (60% for a house) depending on which is lower. In March 2012, the s discount in London was raised to £100,000. The higher discounts mean the receipt will often not be enough to finance a replacement home and in some cases will not cover the debt secured against the property. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]A housing association tenant will have the 
[normal]PRtB
[normal] if they were a local authority tenant when their home was transferred into housing association ownership. The 
[normal]PRtB
[normal] gives tenants the same rights and discounts to buy their homes as local authority tenants. Yet, there are some key differences in how sales receipts are handled:
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]2.3
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The receipt is shared according to the terms of the transfer agreement.[bold] When social housing is transferred from a local authority into a housing association, a transfer agreement is drawn up. Each agreement sets out how any sales receipts will be split. In many cases, the agreement allocates the majority share of the receipt to the local authority with the housing association receiving a smaller share to cover their foregone rental income.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]2.4
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]PRtB[bold] sales receipts are unprotected[bold]. Once the local authority receives its share, they are under no legal obligation to spend the receipts on funding new homes. Government does not monitor the spending of these sales receipts.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.5
[normal] 
[normal]The National Housing 
[normal]Federation  have
[normal] carried out two surveys of housing associations to understand the impact that higher discounts would have on the sector and the supply of affordable homes. These were the key findings:
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]2.5.1
[normal] 
[normal]Sales levels[bold]: the 2012 Right to Buy Impact Assessment estimated that sales would increase by 150% in three years. Surveyed housing associations believe that sales would far exceed this estimate.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]2.5.2
[normal] 
[normal]Transfer agreements[bold]: the vast majority of housing associations entered into agreements whereby they retain a small portion of the receipt to cover foregone rental income. The lion’s share goes to the local authority.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]2.5.3
[normal] 
[normal]Replacement homes[bold]: 92% of respondents declared that they would not be able to replace any homes sold via the 
[normal]PRtB
[normal]. Only two are able to replace homes, because they retain an unusually large share of the sales receipt.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]2.5.4
[normal] 
[normal]Long-term development capacity[bold]:
[normal] 
[normal]60% of housing associations declared that an increase in discounts would affect their long-term financing arrangements
[normal] and ultimately build fewer affordable homes. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.1
[normal] 
[normal]Since the national discount was raised in April 2012, RTB sales have doubled
[normal]. 
[normal]Between April 2012 to March 2013,
[normal] there were nearly
[normal] 6,000 local authority
[normal] RTB sales. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.2
[normal] 
[normal]PRtB
[normal] sales also doubled in the past year. According to the Statistical Data Return (published by the Social Housing Regulator), there were 2462 
[normal]PRtB
[normal] sales compared to 1106 sales in 2011/12.  
[normal]As the Government does not monitor the number of 
[normal]PRtB
[normal] sales on a regular quarterly basis, we do not know the number of 
[normal]PRtB
[normal] sales in each quarter. 
[normal]However, using financial data within the Social Housing Regulator’s quarterly surveys, we can understand the dramatic increase in 
[normal]PRtB
[normal] sales receipts on a quarter by quarter basis, as
[normal] the graph below shows:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal](The Regulator, Quarterly Survey of Providers, August 2013)
[normal]3.3
[normal] 
[normal]Market intelligence from housing associations also indicates that sales levels are significantly rising across the country. The table below combines data from four different housing associations in Greater Manchester, demonstrating the impact that the increased discounts is having on sales and applications:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]PRtB[bold]2010/11[bold]2011/12[bold]2012/13[bold]% Change[bold]11/12 to 12/13[bold]Applications
[normal]135
