[normal]The impact on long-term capacity[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]4.8
[normal] 
[normal]During the course of 2013/14, Phoenix 
[normal]have
[normal] already sold 12 properties via the 
[normal]PRtB
[normal]. These properties were worth £1.8m. They were sold for around £950,000. Under its transfer agreement, Phoenix only retained £250,000 (14% of the property’s value) and the Lewisham Council retained the remaining sales receipt.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.9
[normal] 
[normal]Phoenix 
[normal]expect
[normal] to sell 33 properties in the course of 2012/13, of which 15 would be flats and 18 would be houses. Under this scenario, Phoenix could expect to lose around £5.25m in the value of their asset base in a single year of operation. Moreover, Phoenix will only retain around £750,000 in sales receipts. If they continue to lose their assets at this pace, their asset base will be significantly eroded within a few years. Over time, it will make it harder for them to re-finance existing debts and to take on additional borrowing. If that becomes a reality, they will have less 
[normal]capacity  and
[normal] could stop developing new homes.
[normal]5.1
[normal] 
[normal]With a surge in the number of right to buy sales, housing associations are receiving insufficient sales receipts to replace the homes lost from the sector. As they are not able to build replacement homes, right to buy is eroding their asset base, financial capacity and ability to build new homes. This finding is supported by the Regulator, which stated in the last Quarterly Survey, that housing associations
[normal] [bold]“with high number of transfer properties 
[normal]eligible for preserved RTB may derive some short-term economic benefit, but need to be careful to manage the long-term risk associated with loss of stock.” However, housing associations need more resources to manage these risks. Government intervention is needed now to manage these risks. Otherwise, right to buy discounts will eventually harm the Government ambition to increase the long-term supply of new homes.
[normal]6.1
[normal] 
[normal]T
[normal]he impact of
[normal] the higher national discounts is
[normal] 
[normal]becoming clearer. 
[normal]The Joint Committee should recommend that legislation be amended to:[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]6.1.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Protect Preserved Right to Buy Receipts[bold]: there must be a requirement for councils to spend at least a proportion of their 
[normal]PRtB
[normal] receipts on building new homes. This 
[normal]legislative 
[normal]change would not only help housing associations replace stock lost via the 
[normal]PRtB
[normal], it would also help the Government deliver 
[normal]replace more homes lost via the 
[normal]PRtB
[normal]  
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]6.1.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Incorporate debt within the cost floor[bold]: 
[normal]the higher
[normal] discount
[normal]s
[normal] mean
[normal]s
[normal] that the receipt is
[normal] sometimes
[normal] insufficient to pay down the debt secured against the property. 
[normal]A
[normal]n amendment to the Cost Floor Rules (Se
[normal]ction 131, Housing Act 1985)
[normal] [bold]could allow housing associations to reduce the level of discount if the sales receipt does not cover the debt. This would protect the borrowing arrangements of housing associations. In 
[normal]doing so, it would give them the confidence to continue making long-term investments in improving the quality of their housing stock that are worth millions of pounds.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.2
[normal] 
[normal] [bold]The Joint Committee should also call on Government to:[bold]&#xa0;[bold]6.2.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Carry out an independent right to buy review[bold]: [bold]Government need to commission a review to 
[normal]assess progress and develop a consensus on the measures needed to build more replacement homes
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]6.2.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Put in place a more effective system for monitoring preserved right to buy sales: [bold]Government needs a better understanding of the increased discounts upon preserved right to buy sales levels. A system must regularly monitor sales levels and the number of homes being replaced.
[normal]&#xa0;
